In [58]:
# Inferences
# Survived vs. Pclass (Inverse): A positive correlation exists between passenger class (e.g., first class) and survival, indicating that passengers in higher classes had a higher chance of surviving.
# Survived vs. Fare (Direct): greater fare-paying passengers had greater survival rates, demonstrating a direct correlation between fare and survival.
# Pclass vs. Fare (Inverse): Results showed an inversely direct link between class and fare, with lower passenger class (such as third class) being associated with higher fares.
# Age vs. Pclass (Inverse): Older passengers typically traveled in lower classes, whereas younger passengers were more frequently identified in higher classes, demonstrating an inversely direct association between age and class.
